    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-04-18T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-04-18T11:00:00-05:00" n="66"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d66">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">340.1115A/532: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Denmark</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Atherton</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Copenhagen</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-04-18T17:00:00+01:00"
                            >April 18, 1940—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 8:27 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>105. Department’s 29, April 10, 9 p.m. From the 500 inquiries made it is
                    estimated 123 Americans with valid passports, etc., have sufficient funds to
                    return to the United States. Twenty additional without funds.</p>
                <p>Forty valid American women citizens with Danish husbands or families desire
                    return providing Danish members permitted proceed to the United States. Half of
                    these only possess funds.</p>
                <p>Sixty cases unrebutted presumption including wives and families desire return of
                    whom half have funds.</p>
                <p>Undoubtedly other Americans desiring return who cannot yet communicate with
                    Copenhagen but above named groups alone might require $15,000 for full return
                    fare.</p>
                <p>Families Major Hohenthal<note n="18" xml:id="d66fn18">Maj. William D. Hohenthal,
                        Assistant Military Attaché in Germany.</note> and Consul General Sauer<note
                        n="19" xml:id="d66fn19">Emil Sauer, Consul General at Frankfort on the
                        Main.</note> have received German permission for departure.</p>
                <p>Although various travel agencies here are professedly hopeful of arranging group
                    visas for Americans across Germany to Genoa, the Legation has no assurances as
                    yet to give to American citizens. Local German authorities, however, hopeful
                    they can arrange group visas in due time without reference each individual case
                    to Berlin.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Atherton</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
